06632nam a22007215i 9780773567160DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19981998xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735671607 a10.1515/97807735671602doi  a(DE-B1597)656566  a(OCoLC)1142503873  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aU21.2bC48 1998eb 7aHIS0270002bisacsh04a355.02/091 aEnglish, Allan Douglas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChanging Face of War :bLearning from History /cAllan Douglas English. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1998] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tEditor’s Preface -- tIntroduction -- tThe Evolution of Military Strategy and Doctrine -- tClausewitz and His Influence on U.S. and Canadian Military Doctrine -- tThe Myth of Manoeuvre Warfare: Attrition in Military History -- tStrategy and Technology in Transition: Moltke and the Prussian General Staff -- tA Study in Operational Command: Byng and the Canadian Corps -- tAn Example of Force Development: Tukhachevsky and the Soviet Art of Deep Battle -- tThe Problem of Army Renewal: Seeckt and the Reichswehr -- tUnconventional Warfare -- tMao Zedong: A Peasant Who Learned from History -- tRevolutionary War: The Viet Minh and the First Indo-Chinese War -- tVo Nguyên Giap: A Strategy for Protracted Revolutionary War -- tBrown-Water Navies and Counterinsurgency Operations -- tEliminating the Shadows: Applying Counterinsurgency Doctrine to Peacekeeping -- tConflict in the Twenty-First Century -- tComputers and Strategy: It’s the Thought That Counts -- tStealth Technology: A Revolution in Air Warfare? -- tBeyond the Line: Strategy in Support of Space Control -- tConventional Arms Control and Intelligence: A Symbiotic Relationship -- tThe Statistical Study of War: The Relationship between Democracy and War -- tThe Media and the Conduct of War -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPart I deals with the evolution of military strategy and doctrine, from the Napoleonic Wars to today. Contributors look at the influence of great military thinkers, such as Carl von Clausewitz, on the armed forces of the Western world and examine how previous military leaders dealt with issues similar to those faced today, such as the effects of technology on strategy, the significance of the operational level of war, and ways of restructuring the armed forces in times of uncertainty and change. Part II examines warfare at the end of this century. Examples of the development of revolutionary warfare in Asia from Mao to Giap are used to underscore the cultural and situational influences on doctrines of revolutionary war. Part III looks at the future of conflict in the twenty-first century. Contributors investigate diverse issues, including the impact of computers on warfare, the effect of media coverage on strategy, space policy, arms control in the post-Cold War era, political systems and their relationship to the probability of war, and the prospects of stealth technology. In an era when armed forces around the world have come under increasing scrutiny and criticism, this collection of essays provides valuable lessons that may avert future military mistakes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh1 aAttfield, CAPT Neal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerridge-Sills, Mervyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlank, LCOL Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela